[start section id="20103"]

Mrs. Hildreth is a 58-year-old female who was in her usual state of health until June of 2010 when she was hospitalized with a small-bowel obstruction.  Her symptoms of nausea, vomiting, and abdominal discomfort were treated with conservative measures; and after a number of days, she returned  back to her baseline.
She did quite well without recurrent symptoms until early August of 2010 when she developed persistent and significant rectal bleeding.  For this reason, she underwent a colonoscopy on August 18, 2010.  Per the procedure note, this was a technically difficult study with evidence of a rigid distal sigmoid consistent with postradiation change as well as prominent mucosal folds of the ileocecal valve which were biopsied.  Of note, she also underwent an EGD at this time which revealed grade A erosive esophagitis.  The biopsy results from the ileocecal region revealed low-grade dysplasia with elements of focal high-grade dysplasia.  These findings, in concert with the rectal bleeding, led to a second colonoscopy on August 31, 2010.  During this procedure, an ulcerated mass lesion was noted just proximal to the ileal orifice which appeared to involve the appendix and the appendiceal orifice as well.  This was biopsied, and pathologic review revealed a small focus of invasive moderately differentiated adenocarcinoma arising in the setting of an adenoma with high-grade dysplasia.
Given this finding, Mrs. Hildreth proceeded to the operating room on September 2, 2010, and underwent a laparoscopic-assisted right hemicolectomy with side-to-side ileotransverse colostomy under the care of Dr. Bryant and his team.  The preliminary pathology results from this resection have revealed a T2, N0 adenocarcinoma of the appendix.
Mrs. Hildreth states that she is doing relatively well postoperatively.  She does have some abdominal pain and has yet to pass flatus or stool.  She also has had some nausea but denies fevers, hills, cough, shortness-of-breath, or any other complaint.

[end section id="20103"]

